{
  "text": "It is difficult for physicians to identify 22q11.2 deletion syndrome with certainty because this syndrome shows a wide variability in phenotype expression [CITATION_1] . Additionally, some characteristics such as speech difficulties and learning disabilities are not readily apparent during early infancy [CITATION_2] . Because CHD is generally the first presenting symptom in such patients, molecular screening for 22q11.2 in CHD patients is important in the evaluation of associated noncardiac features [CITATION_3] . The association of CTD with 22q11.2 deletion reminds us that it may be advisable to test for the microdeletion when there is a diagnosis of conotruncal malformation, especially in young infants whose extracardiac features cannot yet be excluded [CITATION_4] .",
  "correct_citation": {
